<body><div class=WordSection1>
<div class="brand">📚 ENGLISH CODING · 영어코딩</div>
<h1>⚡ WD002 Week 4 — English Worksheet</h1>
<p><strong>Topic:</strong> User Input — Talking with Input Boxes · <strong>Course:</strong> Web Dev Basics: JavaScript · <strong>Time:</strong> about 45 minutes</p>
<p>This week the user gets to <strong>type</strong>. An <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> box collects text, and <code>.value</code> reads whatever is inside it. You will grab that value, save it in a variable, show it on the page — and politely warn the user when the box is empty.</p>
<hr />
<h2>1 · Predict 🔮</h2>
<p>Read each piece of code. Before you run it, write what you think will happen.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;input id=&quot;nameBox&quot; type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;
&lt;button id=&quot;show&quot;&gt;Show&lt;/button&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#show&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    let name = document.querySelector(&quot;#nameBox&quot;).value;
    console.log(name);
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The user types <code>Jiwoo</code> and clicks Show. What prints to the console?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;input id=&quot;nameBox&quot; type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&quot;out&quot;&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#go&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    let name = document.querySelector(&quot;#nameBox&quot;).value;
    document.querySelector(&quot;#out&quot;).textContent = &quot;Hi, &quot; + name + &quot;!&quot;;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The user types <code>Ari</code>. What full sentence ends up on the screen?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  let name = document.querySelector(&quot;#nameBox&quot;).value;
  if (name === &quot;&quot;) {
    alert(&quot;Please type something&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The user clicks without typing anything. What happens?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;input id=&quot;ageBox&quot; type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  let age = document.querySelector(&quot;#ageBox&quot;).value;
  console.log(age + 1);
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>The user types <code>10</code>. You might expect <code>11</code>. What actually prints, and why? (Hint: <code>.value</code> is always text.)</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>2 · Spot the Bug 🐛</h2>
<p>Each block was meant to do something, but it is broken. Read what it is <strong>supposed</strong> to do, then rewrite it so it works. After that, explain why the original was wrong and why your fix works.</p>
<p><strong>Bug A</strong> — Clicking should show what the user typed. Right now it always shows the <strong>same</strong> word, no matter what is typed.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;input id=&quot;nameBox&quot; type=&quot;text&quot;&gt;
&lt;h1 id=&quot;out&quot;&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
  document.querySelector(&quot;#show&quot;).addEventListener(&quot;click&quot;, function() {
    document.querySelector(&quot;#out&quot;).textContent = &quot;nameBox&quot;;
  });
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> the code shows the text <code>"nameBox"</code>, not the box's <code>.value</code>. Read the value first.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — This should warn the user when the box is empty. Right now the warning shows even when they <em>did</em> type something.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  let name = document.querySelector(&quot;#nameBox&quot;).value;
  if (name = &quot;&quot;) {
    alert(&quot;Box is empty!&quot;);
  }
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> one equals sign <em>sets</em> a value; you want to <em>compare</em>. How many equals signs do you need to check if two things are the same?</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — This should add two numbers the user types. Right now typing <code>3</code> and <code>4</code> gives <code>34</code> instead of <code>7</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="language-html">&lt;script&gt;
  let a = document.querySelector(&quot;#num1&quot;).value;
  let b = document.querySelector(&quot;#num2&quot;).value;
  console.log(a + b);
&lt;/script&gt;
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>.value</code> hands you text, so <code>+</code> glues the text together. Turn each value into a number first with <code>Number(...)</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>3 · Make It Yours 📸</h2>
<p>Build a page that asks for a <strong>name</strong> and an <strong>age</strong>, then shows a short introduction.</p>
<ol>
<li>Add two input boxes and a button.</li>
<li>When the button is clicked, read both values with <code>.value</code>.</li>
<li>Show a sentence like <code>Hi, I'm ___ and I'm ___ years old.</code> on the page.</li>
<li>If <strong>either</strong> box is empty, show a warning instead of the sentence.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Stretch:</strong> add the age to a number (for example, show "Next year you'll be ___") — remember to turn the value into a <code>Number</code> first.</p>
<p>When you finish, come back here. Send a <strong>photo or video</strong> of both a filled-in result and the empty-box warning, then explain what you did. Use these sentence starters — write 4 to 6 sentences total.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>First, I made input boxes for …</p>
<p>I used <code>.value</code> to …</p>
<p>To check for an empty box, I …</p>
<p>When both boxes are filled, the page shows …</p>
<p>One tricky moment was when …</p>
<p>If I had more time, I would …</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<hr />
<h2>4 · Record Your Walkthrough 🎥</h2>
<p>Take a video on your phone (or a parent's phone) while your page runs. Talk through it like you are teaching someone who has never seen it. Try to use these words: <strong>input</strong>, <strong>value</strong>, <strong>empty</strong>, <strong>warning</strong>, <strong>variable</strong>.</p>
<blockquote>
<ol>
<li>Show the empty boxes, then type into them.</li>
<li>Click the button and show the introduction appear.</li>
<li>Clear a box and show the warning.</li>
<li>Read one line out loud and say where it reads the value.</li>
</ol>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Write what you will say in your video.</strong> Plan it here before you record — you can read from it while filming.</p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

